1. Managing Transactions with @Transactional

Theory
Transaction: A sequence of operations performed as a single unit of work. Either all succeed,
or all fail (rollback).
@Transactional: Annotation used in Spring to declare that a method/class should run within a
transaction.

Implementation

Service Example:

import org.springframework.transaction.annotation.Transactional;

@Service
public class UserService {
    @Transactional
    public void updateUser(User user) {
        userRepository.save(user);
        // If any exception occurs, all changes are rolled back
    }
}

By default, all repository methods are transactional.
You can annotate service methods to ensure all operations inside are part of a single transaction.

2. Transaction Propagation Settings

Theory
Propagation: Defines how transactions behave when a method is called inside another
transactional method.

Common types:

REQUIRED (default): Joins the existing transaction or creates a new one if none exists.
REQUIRES_NEW: Always starts a new transaction, suspending the existing one.
MANDATORY: Must run inside an existing transaction; throws an exception if none exists.
SUPPORTS: Runs in a transaction if one exists; otherwise, runs non-transactionally.
NOT_SUPPORTED: Runs outside of a transaction, suspending any existing one.
NEVER: Throws an exception if a transaction exists.
NESTED: Starts a nested transaction within the current one.

Implementation

Example:

@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
public void createUser(User user) {
    userRepository.save(user);
}
You can set propagation using the propagation attribute in @Transactional.


3. Optimizing Read-Only Transactions

Theory
For query-only operations (no data modification), you can mark transactions as read-only.
This can improve performance by:
Avoiding unnecessary locking.
Allowing the database to optimize for read operations.

Implementation

Example:

@Transactional(readOnly = true)
public List<User> getActiveUsers() {
    return userRepository.findByStatus(Status.ACTIVE);
}

Use readOnly = true for methods that only fetch data.